Liquor Sales in Iowa

This dataset https://data.iowa.gov/Sales-Distribution/2019-Iowa-Liquor-Sales/38x4-vs5h contains the spirits purchase information of Iowa Class “E” liquor licensees by product and date of purchase for 2019. The dataset can be used to analyze total spirits sales in Iowa of individual products at the store level.

  1. The complete dataset is too large. Download and import the alcohol sales data for Ames only:
  1. Go to https://data.iowa.gov/Sales-Distribution/2019-Iowa-Liquor-Sales/38x4-vs5h
  2. Click Filter – Filter – Go advanced now
  3. Add a New Filter Condition: City is Ames.
  4. Export – CSV – Download
  5. Use readr::read_csv to import.
  1. Data cleaning:
  1. extract geographic latitude and longitude from the variable Store Location
  2. make sure the variables are in the correct type, by converting incorrect variable types.
  3. extract year, month and day from the variable Date as separate columns.
ia <- read_csv('2019_Iowa_Liquor_Sales.csv')

ia <- ia %>%
  separate(Date, into = c('month', 'day', 'year'), sep = "/")
ia <- ia %>%
  mutate_at(.vars = vars(month:year),
            .funs = funs(as.numeric))
ia <- ia %>%
  mutate(`Store Location` = substr(`Store Location`, 8, nchar(`Store Location`) - 1))
ia <- ia %>%
  separate(`Store Location`, into = c('lat', 'long'), sep = ' ')
  1. First overview:
  1. Plot a scatterplot of lat and long of store locations.
ia %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = long, y = lat)) +
  geom_point() +
  theme(axis.title = element_blank(),
        axis.text = element_blank())

  1. Provide a visual breakdown of the liquor category (by Category Name). Include volume sold in the breakdown.
ia %>%
  filter(!is.na(`Category Name`)) %>%
  group_by(`Category Name`) %>%
  summarize(volume = sum(`Volume Sold (Gallons)`)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = `Category Name`, y = volume)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  coord_flip() +
  theme(axis.text.y = element_text(size = 6))

  1. Find the daily sales liquor sales in Ames in 2019. Summarize the number of sales, volume of liquor sold, and amount of money spent.
ia %>%
  group_by(month, day) %>%
  summarize(num_sales = n(), total_volume = sum(`Volume Sold (Gallons)`),
            total_money = sum(`Sale (Dollars)`)) -> ia_daily

ia_daily %>%
  arrange(desc(total_volume))

ia_daily <- ia_daily %>%
  mutate(date = paste(month, day, "2019", sep = "/"))

ia_daily <- ia_daily %>%
  mutate(date = mdy(date))
ia_daily %>%
